Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips
and pop onto a #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until soft and slightly charred,
~{15-18%minutes}.

Meanwhile, trim the @baby gem lettuce{1} and halve lengthways, then thinly slice.

Crush the @salted peanuts{25%g} in the unopened sachet using a #rolling pin{}.

When the peppers are halfway through cooking, heat a large #frying pan{} on
medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @British beef mince{240%g} and fry until browned,
~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks, then drain and discard
any excess fat.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. It's cooked
> when no longer pink in the middle.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Once the mince is cooked, add the @Thai style spice mix{1} (add less if you'd
prefer things milder) and @ginger, garlic & lemongrass puree{15%g}. Stir-fry for
~{30%seconds}.

Pour in the @ketjap manis{25%ml} and @water{for the beef}.

Stir together until slightly thickened and nicely glazed, ~{1-2%minutes}, then
remove from the heat.

A couple of mins before you're ready to serve, pop the @plain taco tortillas{6}
onto a baking tray and into the oven to warm through, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Share the baby gem between your tortillas.

Top with the roasted pepper and glazed mince - as much as you'd like.

Sprinkle with the peanuts to finish.

> TIP: Tacos are best enjoyed eaten by hand - get stuck in!

Serve with @mayonnaise{3}.